<div id="review_3878788967" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3878788967" />
    <a title="Swaroop" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/100264072-swaroop"><img alt="Swaroop" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621672092p2/100264072.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3878788967?book_show_action=true">Mar 07, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Swaroop" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Swaroop" href="/user/show/100264072-swaroop">Swaroop</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3878788967" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2538549959145702284"><b>A timeless masterpiece!</b><br/><br/><i>&quot;Like the kaleidoscope, they augmented themselves with their turning and found light from irrelevant and accidental sources.&quot;</i><br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1615224947i/30981777.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/><i>&quot;…there he hesitated for a moment, to turn first one way and another, as the needle of a compass, slow to settle, discovers its point.&quot;</i><br/><br/>Set in 1873, John Williams’ <i>Butcher`s Crossing</i> is centred around the story of William Andrews, who leaves his hometown Boston, quits studying at Havard College and travels to the Kansas town of Butcher`s Crossing. <br/><br/><i>&quot;…h</i></span>
  <span id="freeText2538549959145702284" style="display:none"><b>A timeless masterpiece!</b><br><br><i>"Like the kaleidoscope, they augmented themselves with their turning and found light from irrelevant and accidental sources."</i><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1615224947i/30981777.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><i>"…there he hesitated for a moment, to turn first one way and another, as the needle of a compass, slow to settle, discovers its point."</i><br><br>Set in 1873, John Williams’ <i>Butcher`s Crossing</i> is centred around the story of William Andrews, who leaves his hometown Boston, quits studying at Havard College and travels to the Kansas town of Butcher`s Crossing. <br><br><i>"…he realized quite suddenly that it was some irony such as this that had driven him from Harvard College, from Boston, and thrust him into this strange world where he felt unaccountably at home."</i><br><br>Will finds himself uncomfortable in the urban sophisticated habitat and decides to discover himself in the open wild. He finds about a businessman known to his father, who deals in buffalo skins and hides. Will strikes a deal with the businessman, builds a team with the help of a buffalo hunter, pays for the tools and infrastructure, and sets off on a buffalo-hunting expedition in the Colorado territory. <br><br>Even though the central theme seems to be about Will ‘finding himself’, this timeless and descriptive masterpiece of John Williams holds so much more – the brilliant description of the landscape, the vivid portrayal of the human endeavour and resilience to survive, and the close attention to the characters and events. <br><br><i>"He believed - and had believed for a long time - that there was a subtle magnetism in nature, which, if he unconsciously yielded to it, would direct him alright."</i><br><br><i>Butcher`s Crossing</i> speaks about the wildness of nature, man`s quest to conquer and tame the wild, and the destruction and devastation that follows because of the human ego to dominate and pillage. The story also highlights mankind`s attempts to control and ravage not just nature but also women. <br><br>The desire and path of self-discovery will always remain unfulfilled when men do not consider and understand that women ‘complete’ them, and they are not one of their objects of conquering and acquire like the buffalo skins.<br> <br><blockquote>“You get born, and you nurse on lies, and you get weaned on lies, and you learn fancier lies in school. You live all your life on lies, and then maybe when you’re ready to die, it comes to you—that there’s nothing, nothing but yourself and what you could have done. Only you ain’t done it, because the lies told you there was something else. Then you know you could of had the world, because you’re the only one that knows the secret; only then it’s too late. You’re too old.”</blockquote><br>-----<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1621632490i/31367086.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><i>“Buffalo never dies of old age. He’s either killed by a man or dragged down by a wolf.”</i> <br><br>In <i>Butcher`s Crossing</i>, Will and his group slaughter thousands of buffaloes within few days. <br>In the middle of the 19th century, there were an estimated <b>50 million buffalo</b> roaming the plains. In order to develop the lands, particularly for the railroads, men were hired to kill the buffalo. An estimated 200,000 buffalo were killed every year. Hunters began killing them by the thousands for their hides, and by the end of the 19th century, only <b>300 buffalo</b> were left in the wild plains [Source - <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/where-the-buffalo-no-longer-roamed-3067904/">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/histor...</a>]. <br><br>-----<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1621632490i/31367087._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>[John Williams, <b>The Man Who Wrote the Perfect Novel</b>, <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.ft.com/content/573d6466-f7be-11e8-a154-2b65ddf314e9">https://www.ft.com/content/573d6466-f...</a>]<br><br>Now, eagerly, looking forward to reading the 3rd masterpiece [<i>Augustus</i>] by John Williams.<br><br><i>Stoner, Butcher`s Crossing</i> and <i>Augustus</i>.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2538549959145702284" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

