  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4381417495" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4381417495" />
    <a title="Nora Kovacs" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/76908776-nora-kovacs"><img alt="Nora Kovacs" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1619140282p2/76908776.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4381417495?book_show_action=true">Dec 19, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nora Kovacs" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nora Kovacs" href="/user/show/76908776-nora-kovacs">Nora Kovacs</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4381417495" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12023579949412461550">Just like Will Andrews in the last chapter, I find myself standing in the middle of Miller&apos;s holocaust trying to make sense of it all.<br/> <br/>Andrews, a Harvard dropout, arrives to the west with a vague idea of Emersonian transcendentalism, naively believing that getting to know the wilderness is the answer to his questions. When an old family acquaintance from Boston, McDonald, offers him work he refuses, choosing to go on a hunt with Miller instead who had long dreamed of killing the elusive Colorado</span>
  <span id="freeText12023579949412461550" style="display:none">Just like Will Andrews in the last chapter, I find myself standing in the middle of Miller's holocaust trying to make sense of it all.<br /> <br />Andrews, a Harvard dropout, arrives to the west with a vague idea of Emersonian transcendentalism, naively believing that getting to know the wilderness is the answer to his questions. When an old family acquaintance from Boston, McDonald, offers him work he refuses, choosing to go on a hunt with Miller instead who had long dreamed of killing the elusive Colorado buffalos he once saw 10 years ago. Their journey is a tour de force of first experiences for Andrews.<br /><br />Williams’ minutely detailed chronicle of their ordeals, gratuitous description of butchering and cruelty hidden under the mist of mesmerizing nature descriptions are there to distract us for as long as possible and delay the inevitable tragedy, which when it finally happens, feels like a great release. Butcher’s Crossing is the bookish version of tantric sex.<br />After our well-deserved climax, Williams grants his characters closure as well. When Miller sees his long-time dream, as well as his livelihood, go up in flames, he turns the metaphor into reality and burns down McDonald’s property, and rides away into the darkness, but not before giving Andrews one last lesson about betrayal, friendship, and humility. The satisfaction this gives him, and the stench of the burning hides is his closure. <br /><br />McDonald plans to go back east and continue exploiting the west from a safe distance.<br /><br />As for Andrews, he decides to leave all his money for the prostitute he befriended, sneak out and ride away into the nothingness as aimlessly as he came. He learned nothing that could turn his misery into a shape accepted by the civilized society he comes from. <br /><br />“He would not return with McDonald to his home, to the country that had given him birth, had raised him in the shape he occupied and the condition that he had only begun to recognize, and that had relinquished him to the wilderness in which he had thought to find a truer shape of himself. No he would never return.”<br /><br />Both Miller and Andrews ride away, but you are left with the feeling that to one of them, what happens next, does not matter.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12023579949412461550" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


